    "summary": "The Viking raid on Lindisfarne (June 8, 793 AD) — a surprise attack on the holy island monastery off the Northumbrian coast of northeastern England — is the conventional starting point of the [[event:88|Viking Age]]. Norse longships appeared without warning, killing monks, looting the monastery's treasures (gold, silver, and gems accumulated over a century of royal patronage), and carrying off monks as slaves. The attack shocked the Christian world: Lindisfarne was one of the most revered religious sites in Britain, the home of the Lindisfarne Gospels and the site of St. Cuthbert's shrine, and its violation by pagan Northmen seemed an apocalyptic omen to contemporaries.\n\nThe scholar Alcuin of York (at Charlemagne's court) wrote a letter to the Northumbrian king expressing horror: 'Never before has such terror appeared in Britain as we have now suffered from a pagan race.' The attack's impact on contemporaries' imagination was disproportionate to its physical scale — it was not the first Norse raid on Britain and was no more violent than many Christian-on-Christian raids of the era. But its targeting of a famous holy site, the paganism of the attackers, and the dramatic sea-borne surprise gave it totemic status. The [[event:2197|Book of Kells]] was reportedly produced partly in response to the Viking threat to Iona monastery, another major holy site raided in 795 AD. Lindisfarne became a symbol of Christian vulnerability to pagan violence, making it the perfect marker for the Viking Age's beginning in historical memory.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindisfarne#Raid_of_793",
